This paper deals with game theory and mechanism design, which are central topics in computer science. Specifically, it studies sequential versions of two feasible Groves mechanisms used for single item auctions, which falls under the category of algorithmic game theory (cs.GT). The paper also introduces natural optimal strategies, which can be seen as a form of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper uses mathematical optimization techniques to maximize social welfare, which is a common theme in machine learning (cs.LG) and data science (cs.DS). Finally, the paper deals with multi-agent systems and coordination, which is a topic in multi-agent systems (cs.MA).
